  "local_port": 43214,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How do I prepare myself for screening?",
  "response": "Preparing for a screening depends on the type (e.g., job interview, medical exam, security check), but here\u2019s a **general guide** with tailored tips for common scenarios:\n\n---\n\n### **General Preparation Steps**\n1. **Understand the Purpose**  \n   Confirm what the screening involves (e.g., skills test, health check, background review). Ask the organizer for details if unsure.\n\n2. **Research Requirements**  \n   Review instructions (e.g., documents to bring, pre-screening tasks like fasting for medical tests, or technical setups for online assessments).\n\n3. **Organize Documents**  \n   Gather IDs, resumes, medical records, certificates, or references ahead of time. Keep digital copies handy if needed.\n\n4. **Mental/Physical Readiness**  \n   - Rest well the night before.  \n   - Eat lightly (if allowed) to stay focused.  \n   - Practice relaxation techniques (e.g., deep breathing) to manage stress.\n\n5. **Practice Communication**  \n   Rehearse answers to common questions (for interviews) or explanations of your background/goals. Be concise and honest.\n\n6. **Logistics Check**  \n   Plan travel/parking for in-person screenings. Test tech (internet, camera, software) for virtual ones. Arrive early.\n\n---\n\n### **Scenario-Specific Tips**\n#### **1. Job/Interview Screening**  \n   - Research the company\u2019s mission, values, and recent news.  \n   - Review the job description and align your skills with the role.  \n   - Prepare examples using the **STAR method** (Situation, Task, Action, Result).  \n   - Practice mock interviews with a friend or via recording.  \n   - Bring extra resumes, a notebook, and questions for the interviewer.  \n\n#### **2. Medical Screening**  \n   - Follow pre-test instructions (e.g., fasting, avoiding medications).  \n   - Wear comfortable clothing for physical exams.  \n   - Share your full medical history and current symptoms honestly.  \n   - Ask about risks, next steps, or how to receive results.  \n\n#### **3. Security Screening (e.g., Airport/Event)**  \n   - Check prohibited items (liquids, electronics, tools) in advance.  \n   - Wear easy-to-remove shoes/jackets. Keep IDs/boarding passes accessible.  \n   - Follow instructions promptly to avoid delays.  \n\n#### **4. Academic/Program Screening**  \n   - Review application materials (essays, portfolios) and be ready to discuss them.  \n   - Prepare to explain your goals and how the program aligns with them.  \n   - For exams, practice with sample questions and time yourself.  \n\n#### **5. Technical Screening (e.g., Coding Test)**  \n   - Practice problem-solving on platforms like LeetCode or HackerRank.  \n   - Clarify the tools/languages allowed. Test your setup (IDE, internet).  \n   - Explain your thought process aloud during the assessment.  \n\n---\n\n### **Post-Screening Follow-Up**  \n- Send a **thank-you email** (for job/academic screenings) within 24 hours.  \n- Reflect on feedback to improve for future screenings.  \n- Track results and next steps (e.g., medical reports, interview rounds).  \n\nBy tailoring your approach to the screening type and staying organized, you\u2019ll feel more confident and reduce surprises! Let me know if you need specifics for your situation.",
